    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Copy-naturality: f is deterministic iff f;copy = copy;(f⊗f)

(define (copy x) (cons x x))

(define (double x) (* x 2))

; Deterministic: apply then copy = copy then apply
(define lhs (copy (double 5)))
(define rhs (cons (double 5) (double 5)))

(display "double: f;copy = ") (display lhs) (newline)
(display "double: copy;f⊗f = ") (display rhs) (newline)
(display "equal? ") (display (equal? lhs rhs))
; #t — deterministic
`} />

    <details class="my-2">
      <summary class="text-xs text-gray-500 cursor-pointer">imperative equivalent</summary>
      <Repl client:load initialCode={`# Copy-naturality in Python (with randomness demo)
import random

copy = lambda x: (x, x)
double = lambda x: x * 2

# Deterministic: both paths agree
print(f"double: {copy(double(5))} == {(double(5), double(5))}")

# Stochastic: paths diverge
def coin(x):
    return x if random.random() > 0.5 else -x

for _ in range(4):
    a, b = coin(5), coin(5)
    print(f"  coin: ({a}, {b}) — {'=' if a==b else '≠'}")
`} />
    </details>

    <!-- Kleisli composition -->
    <h3>Kleisli composition</h3>
    <p>Morphisms in FinStoch compose via <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kleisli_category">🅦 Kleisli composition</a>: feed the output distribution of f into g, marginalizing over the intermediate. This is <code>>>=</code> (bind) from monads.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Kleisli composition: f >=> g
; A distribution is a list of (value . probability) pairs.
; Composition marginalizes the intermediate.

(define (kleisli f g)
  (lambda (x)
    (apply append
      (map (lambda (pair)
        (let ((y (car pair)) (py (cdr pair)))
          (map (lambda (qpair)
            (cons (car qpair) (* py (cdr qpair))))
          (g y))))
      (f x)))))

; f: 50% stay, 50% increment
(define (f x) (list (cons x 0.5) (cons (+ x 1) 0.5)))

; g: double with certainty
(define (g y) (list (cons (* y 2) 1.0)))

; Compose: (f >=> g)(3)
(display ((kleisli f g) 3))
; ((6 . 0.5) (8 . 0.5))
`} />

    <details class="my-2">
      <summary class="text-xs text-gray-500 cursor-pointer">imperative equivalent</summary>
      <Repl client:load initialCode={`# Same thing in Python

def f(x):
    return {x: 0.5, x + 1: 0.5}

def g(y):
    return {y * 2: 1.0}

def kleisli(f, g):
    def composed(x):
        result = {}
        for y, py in f(x).items():
            for z, pz in g(y).items():
                result[z] = result.get(z, 0) + py * pz
        return result
    return composed

print(f"(f >=> g)(3) = {kleisli(f, g)(3)}")
`} />
    </details>

    <!-- Support -->
    <h3>Support — which outputs are possible</h3>
    <p>The <strong>support</strong> of a distribution is the set of outcomes with nonzero probability. Fritz uses support to define possibilistic reasoning — forget the probabilities, just ask "can this happen?"</p>
    <p>This connects to <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/fritz-perrone-2021/">🍞 Fritz, Perrone, Rezagholi 2021</a>, where support becomes a monad morphism.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Support: collapse probabilities to reachability
; supp(dist) = the set of values with nonzero probability

(define (support dist)
  (map car (filter (lambda (p) (> (cdr p) 0)) dist)))

(define (f x)
  (list (cons x 0.7) (cons (+ x 1) 0.2) (cons (+ x 2) 0.1)))

(display (support (f 5)))
; (5 6 7) — these are the possible outputs
`} />

    <details class="my-2">
      <summary class="text-xs text-gray-500 cursor-pointer">imperative equivalent</summary>
      <Repl client:load initialCode={`# Support in Python

def f(x):
    return {x: 0.7, x+1: 0.2, x+2: 0.1}

def support(dist):
    return {k for k, v in dist.items() if v > 0}

print(f"f(5) = {f(5)}")
print(f"support(f(5)) = {support(f(5))}")
`} />
    </details>

    <!-- Informativeness -->
    <h3>Informativeness preorder</h3>
    <p>Fritz defines when one morphism is "more informative" than another: f ≤ g if g factors through f. If you can recover g's output from f's output via post-processing, then f is at least as informative. This is the categorical version of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sufficient_statistic">🅦 sufficient statistics</a>.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Informativeness: f ≤ g if g factors through f
; "f is at least as informative as g"

(define (full-data x) (list (cons (cons x (* x x)) 1.0)))
(define (just-square x) (list (cons (* x x) 1.0)))
(define (post-process pair) (list (cons (cdr (car pair)) 1.0)))

; full-data(-3) = ((-3 . 9) . 1.0)
; post-process recovers just-square
(display (full-data -3)) (newline)
(display (just-square -3)) (newline)
; full-data ≥ just-square: you can post-process to recover the square
; but not the reverse: just-square loses the sign
`} />

    <details class="my-2">
      <summary class="text-xs text-gray-500 cursor-pointer">imperative equivalent</summary>
      <Repl client:load initialCode={`# Informativeness in Python
full_data = lambda x: {(x, x**2): 1.0}
just_square = lambda x: {x**2: 1.0}

print(f"full_data(-3) = {full_data(-3)}")
print(f"just_square(-3) = {just_square(-3)}")
print("full_data ≥ just_square — recoverable")
print("just_square loses the sign — not recoverable")
`} />
    </details>

    <!-- The pipeline connection -->
    <h3>Where this lives in the pipeline</h3>
    <p>The Natural Framework's pipeline is a Kleisli composition in FinStoch. Each stage — Perceive, Cache, Filter, Attend, Remember — is a morphism in this category. Filter is deterministic (copy-natural). Attend is stochastic (must be, by the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pigeonhole_principle">🅦 pigeonhole argument</a>). The informativeness preorder tracks how much information survives each stage.</p>
    <p>This is the ambient category. Everything else — <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/staton-2025/">🍞 Hoare logic</a>, <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/baez-fritz-2011/">🍞 entropy</a>, <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/gaboardi-2021/">🍞 graded types</a> — lives on top of it.</p>

